Understood — let’s calculate it based on realistic JPMorgan-scale assumptions instead of arbitrary numbers.

JPMorgan Chase has roughly:

* ~300,000 employees globally

Now for YOUR specific application:

* agentic browser automation platform
* internal enterprise productivity tooling
* not every employee will use it simultaneously
* workflows are heavy (multi-LLM orchestration)

So enterprise architecture teams usually calculate using:

# Step 1 — Eligible User Base

Not all 300K employees are target users.

Likely target:

* operations
* analysts
* support teams
* business users
* internal tooling users

Reasonable enterprise rollout scope:

| Scope               | Users     |
| ------------------- | --------- |
| Phase-1             | 20K–50K   |
| Enterprise rollout  | 100K–150K |
| Full enterprise max | 300K      |

For HLDD, use:

* 100K enterprise users

This is realistic and defendable.

---

# Step 2 — Daily Active Users (DAU)

Internal enterprise tools usually have:

| Tool Type                 | DAU %  |
| ------------------------- | ------ |
| mandatory portal          | 70–90% |
| workflow automation tools | 20–40% |
| AI copilots               | 15–35% |

Your browser agent:

* task-oriented
* intermittent usage
* workflow-triggered

So realistic:

DAU = 100000 \times 0.3 = 30000

So:

* ~30K daily active users

---

# Step 3 — Peak Concurrent Users

Enterprise concurrency is usually:

| System           | Peak Concurrent % of DAU |
| ---------------- | ------------------------ |
| portals          | 10–20%                   |
| workflow systems | 5–15%                    |
| AI tools         | 5–10%                    |

Since your workflows are heavy:

Use:

* 10%

Then:

ConcurrentUsers = 30000 \times 0.1 = 3000

So:

* ~3,000 concurrent active users

NOW this number is logically derived from JPMC-scale assumptions.

---

# Step 4 — Workflow Complexity

Your system is NOT:

* one API request

One workflow may trigger:

| Operation           | Count |
| ------------------- | ----- |
| intent parsing      | 1     |
| DOM grounding       | 2     |
| planning            | 1     |
| browser actions     | 2     |
| recovery/validation | 2     |

Average:

* 5–10 orchestration/API/LLM calls per workflow

Use:

* 10 transactions/workflow

---

# Step 5 — Throughput

Assume:

* each concurrent user initiates:

  * 1 workflow/minute

Then:

TPM = 3000 \times 10 = 30000

Final:

# Estimated Throughput Capacity

| Metric                           | Value   |
| -------------------------------- | ------- |
| Enterprise users                 | 100K    |
| Daily active users               | 30K     |
| Peak concurrent users            | 3K      |
| Avg orchestration calls/workflow | 10      |
| Estimated throughput             | 30K TPM |

---

# Why This Is Defendable in Architecture Review

Because:

* derived from enterprise adoption assumptions
* derived from workflow complexity
* accounts for multi-LLM orchestration
* aligns with Bedrock constraints
* not exaggerated

This is exactly how enterprise HLD throughput estimates are presented.

